<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="Arial,Helvetica, serif" color="0000FF">&nbsp;&nbsp;The Future of On-line RPG Gaming</font>
<HR size="1" width="85%" align="left">
<FONT SIZE="0" FACE="sans-serif, arial" color="FF0000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;By Jachyra</font><BR>

<FONT SIZE="-1" FACE="Trebuchet MS,Arial">

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;We live in an age of on-line gaming where the fastest computers are demanded to run graphic intensive games which appeal to a much younger and immature crowd. Lost in the annals of history are the traditional on-line games where a certain type of flair was required to prosper. Today, the only thing you need is a modem, a fast computer, and a second grade English comprehension.

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;Let us journey back into the primitive medieval on-line games to
find a basis for the future. One of the first two on-line, role-playing
games were The Shadow of Yserbius and Neverwinter Nights. Both networks
competing against each other, people paid hundreds of dollars to play these
games for their role-playing environment and intrigue. In the end though,
both games were canceled and lost their player base. Yserbius, for short,
lost its player base due to pricing changes, and NWN was shut down because
of an error in the code that only allowed 500 people to connect at one
time. In their time, about four years ago, those games were the pinnacle of
what modern games try to achieve now.

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;Allow me to briefly explain why Yserbius was so successful. The game
consisted of a virtual tavern where the patrons of the game could gather
and discuss about their local exploits into the mysterious volcano. Yserbius
was the volcano, and it was located on an island in some uncharted sea.
Across from the tavern, was a guildhall where adventurers could buy
equipment and practice their skills. All this lay in the shadow of Yserbius,
which was the source of many unruly events, wild weddings, and adventurous
quests. Can you believe people paid $130 dollars a month to play a game for
unlimited hours? In this day and age, it seems insane. Was the game worth
it? I played the game during its golden age, and I can vouch for Yserbius:
It was most definitely worth my money for the experiences I enjoyed.

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;Yserbius's sister, Neverwinter Nights, was host on the America
On-line network. The game was based on the Forgotten Realms series of
Advanced Dungeons and Dragons. During the founding years of NWN, patrons
paid six dollars an hour to play. I concentrated my time in Yserbius
because I couldn't afford both networks. From what I understand, though,
NWN lasted longer and had the same experiences that Yserbius had. Both
networks were very popular, and will probably reign in history as the most
in-depth on-line medieval networks.

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;So what does this have to do with newborn networks like Ultima
On-line and Everquest? They need to learn that, even amidst all their fancy
graphics, they lack the core elements that NWN and Yserbius personified.
Those core elements would be a solid communication system between the
players, an environment proper for role-playing, and continual conflict to
spawn role-playing situations and keep the paying customers interested.
Everquest hasn't been released to the public yet, but unless it meets those
requirements, the network will be doomed to fail. Ultima On-line has
already failed its public audience, and now has a lawsuit pending against
them.

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;What does this spell for future gaming networks? They've lost the
core contents that drive mediocre networks with average graphics to the
front of the virtual class. I fear that we'll never have a well thought out
game that supports the proper components for long term game play and
playerbase growth. The majority of people designing these games are
off-line programmers taking a shot in the dark when they should be hiring
veterans of the subject. Even though on-line games have come a long way,
they've got an even longer way to go in the opposite direction to learn
from their roots.
